		<header>
			
			<h1>Maize shortages and rising prices projected in Kenya</h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 February 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the USDA, Kenya’s maize production for the 2013/14 marketing year will be 2.8 million tonnes, compared to production in 2012/13 of 3.2 million tonnes and a 5-year average of 3 million tonnes. The decline in production is attributed to:</p>
<ul>

<li>“poor yields due to delayed and inadequate supply of subsidized fertilizers and certified seeds”;</li>

<li>“below average rainfall”;</li>

<li>an “outbreak of the Maize Lethal Necrosis (MLN) disease” and infestation by the Striga parasitic weed; </li>

<li>increased post-harvest losses linked to poor storage and drying facilities; and</li>

<li>early sales of green maize.</li>

</ul>
<p>Kenya is set to increase maize imports to 800,000 tonnes during the year July 2013 to June 2014. USDA implies that a maize supply crisis could occur in Kenya given:</p>
<ul>

<li>the import ban on genetically modified (GM) maize; </li>

<li>inadequate supplies of non-GM exportable maize in the COMESA region (given reported export bans in Malawi and Zambia);</li>

<li>the greater attractiveness of the South Sudan market for Ugandan maize exporters;</li>

<li>the increasing attractiveness of DRC markets for Tanzanian maize exporters; </li>

<li>the application of a 50% <i>ad valorem</i> tariff for non-COMESA-sourced maize.</li>

</ul>
<p>According to the USDA analysis, in view of the current policy measures and regional market developments, it is unclear how Kenya can avert the looming maize shortage. While maize prices were expected to be stable through to 2014, USDA anticipates that “prices will continue to increase” from mid March, as stocks reduce prior to the new harvest in July 2014.</p><p>According to USDA, normal market price developments are being distorted by government procurement programmes: purchases for the strategic grain reserve are being planned at 20% above the market price.</p><p>Against this backdrop, the USDA expects the Kenyan government to waive the 50% duty on extra-COMESA maize imports in the coming months.</p><p><b>Kenyan maize production, imports, consumption and ending stocks</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="154" valign="top">  &nbsp;
  </td><td width="154" valign="top">  2011/12
  </td><td width="154" valign="top">  2012/13
  </td><td width="154" valign="top">  2013/14
  </td>
</tr>

