<p>Source: USDA, ‘Kenya: Corn update report’, 2 December 2013 (see below)</p><p>Meanwhile, it has been reported that late rains have raised the moisture content of maize delivered to National Cereals and Produce Board (NCPB) depots above the 13.5% threshold required to minimise the risk of aflatoxin contamination. This has led to the depots rejecting more deliveries than the previous season: one depot rejected 30% of deliveries, up from 20% the previous season. The farmers affected have then had to sell to traders at prices reportedly between 24 and 33% below the NCPB price.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA, ‘Kenya: Corn update report’, <i>GAIN Report</i>, 2 December 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Kenya%20Corn%20Update%20Report%20_Nairobi_Kenya_12-2-2013.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Kenya%20Corn%20Upd...</a></p><p><i>Business Daily Africa</i>, ‘Farmers hit as NCPB rejects maize’, 6 January 2014</p><p>
<a href="http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Farmers-hit-as-NCPB-rejects-maize/-/539546/2136520/-/rby55z/-/index.html" target="_self">http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Farmers-hit-as-NCPB-rejects-maize/-/5...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The difficulties faced in Kenya in procuring maize from suppliers within the EAC and the application of export restrictions by COMESA suppliers on non-GM maize raise questions as to the coherence and effectiveness of regional policies for developing intra-regional supply chains. Questions arise as to what specific arrangements are required within the EAC and COMESA to facilitate intra-regional trade in maize and build sustainable intra-regional maize supply chains.</p><p>On the trade side, a critical issue would appear to be the need for an effective enforcement mechanism for regional trade agreements, with measures being taken to ensure full respect for agreed commitments (i.e. preventing the use of import and export bans and other non-tariff tools that undermine the development of intra-regional supply chains). </p><p>A range of initiatives have been launched, including COMESA’s regional ‘maize without borders’ policy. This was initially supported by USAID through the Regional Agricultural Trade Expansion Support (RATES) project. However, as the USAID funding came to an end, the initiative was abandoned. This type of experience, where donor-funded pilot projects to strengthen regional cereal supply chains are allowed to lapse once the initial funding runs out, highlights the need for national governments to take ownership and financial responsibility for regional initiatives.</p><p>This is also a need to mobilise investment in expanded maize production in countries such as Malawi and Zambia, in order to ensure a sustainable marketable surplus. At present, the variability of supply leads to pressures to reintroduce export restrictions whenever there is any prospect of a shortfall. However, the link between trade and investment is complex, with export controls weakening intra-regional supply chains and hence undermining investment in production for regional markets.</p><p>Greater coherence between trade and investment policies is required if the conditions are to be created for sustainable intra-regional supply chains.</p>
		</div>
		
